Authorization of appropriations for United States Customs Service for enhanced activities along the Southwest border. Authorization of appropriations for enhanced border investigative resources on the Southwest border, including funds for salaries, expenses, and equipment for the United States Customs Service. This includes specific amounts allocated for fiscal years 2002 and 2003, with additional funding as needed in subsequent years. Authorization of appropriations for salaries, expenses, and equipment for the United States Customs Service on the Southwest border, with specific amounts allocated for fiscal years 2002 and 2003, and additional funding as needed in subsequent years. $158,320,000 from the fiscal year 2002 allocation is designated for technology implementation and deployment along the Southwest border. $158,320,000 from fiscal year 2002 funds allocated for acquisition and deployment of narcotics enforcement, cargo processing, and counterterrorism technology along the Southwest border, including mobile truck gamma ray systems, high energy pallet gamma ray systems, higher energy truck x-ray upgrades, and contract nonintrusive inspection equipment operators. The allocation of $158,320,000 from fiscal year 2002 funds for technology deployment along the Southwest border includes mobile truck gamma ray systems, high energy pallet gamma ray systems, higher energy truck x-ray upgrades, contract nonintrusive inspection equipment operators, canine kennel construction, replacement of canines, and automated targeting systems maintenance. $12,000,000 for nonintrusive inspection technology maintenance;
$800,000 for expansion of Industry Partnership Programs;
$1,600,000 for canine kennel construction;
$500,000 for replacement of canines;
$1,000,000 for automated targeting systems maintenance;
$2,500,000 for 10 x-ray vans;
$1,500,000 for 15 tool trucks;
$3,500,000 to refurbish and maintain existing x-ray vans and tool trucks;
$600,000 for 50 contraband detection kits;
$1,000,000 for 20 remote watch surveillance camera systems. Maintenance funding includes $2,500,000 for x-ray vans, $1,500,000 for tool trucks, $3,500,000 for refurbishing existing vehicles, $600,000 for contraband detection kits, $1,000,000 for surveillance systems, $2,500,000 for truck license plate readers, $1,600,000 for narcotics detectors, $14,800,000 for vehicle targeting systems, and $3,000,000 for under vehicle inspection systems. $1,500,000 for outbound passenger facilities and canopies, $1,500,000 for work station replacements, $3,500,000 for lane installations of Customs Automated Operations System, $5,800,000 for explosive vapor trace detectors. In addition to the previous allocations, $3,000,000 is designated for 250 under vehicle inspection systems, $420,000 for 300 radiation pager detectors, $720,000 for 90 radiation identification devices, and $180,000 for radiation and explosive detection training. In addition to previous allocations, $3,000,000 is designated for 250 under vehicle inspection systems, $420,000 for 300 radiation pager detectors, $720,000 for 90 radiation identification devices, and $180,000 for radiation and explosive detection training. $15,832,000 shall be available each fiscal year for maintenance and support of equipment and training personnel based on 10% of equipment cost. The Commissioner of Customs may use authorized funds for equipment other than specified in subsection (b) if technologically superior. The Commissioner of Customs can use authorized funds for equipment that is technologically superior and achieves the same results at a lower cost than specified equipment. The Commissioner of Customs can reallocate funds, up to 10% of specified amounts, for equipment that achieves the same results at a lower cost than authorized equipment. The Commissioner of Customs can reallocate funds, up to 10% of specified amounts, for equipment specified in paragraphs (1) through (26) of subsection (b) for fiscal years 2002 and 2003. In fiscal years 2002 and 2003, $79,000,000 and $172,000,000 respectively will be allocated for increasing staff at the Southwest border to reduce waiting times and enhance drug enforcement efforts. In fiscal years 2002 and 2003, there will be a net increase of 419 inspectors, 90 special agents, 88 canine enforcement officers, and 280 general support positions for the Southwest border to reduce waiting times at points of entry to no more than 20 minutes and intensify efforts against drug smuggling and money laundering organizations. Additionally, $230,000,000 will be allocated for ports of entry infrastructure improvement. In fiscal years 2002 and 2003, there will be a net increase of personnel to reduce waiting times at points of entry to no more than 20 minutes and intensify efforts against drug smuggling and money laundering organizations. $230,000,000 will be available for ports of entry infrastructure improvement on the Southwest Border. In fiscal years 2002 and 2003, $230,000,000 is authorized for Customs Service facilities construction, improvement, and expansion at Southwest Border ports of entry. This amount is in addition to other appropriations for the Customs Service by law.
